markets.title: Will 2021 be the **hottest year on record**?
markets.ranged_group_name: The mean Land-Ocean Temperature Index value reported by NASA’s Goddard Institute for Space Studies (“GISS”). Specifically, the non-smoothed value of the Land-Ocean Temperature Index.
markets.settle_details: If the global average temperature increases by more than 2.124℉ from 1880 to 2021, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see Rule 100.7 in the Rulebook for details.
markets.description_context: 2020 was tied with 2016 as the hottest year on record. The world’s eight hottest years have all occurred in the 2010s, and with carbon emissions continuing to rise, there’s a chance that 2021 will be the hottest year yet.
markets.description_case_yes: Annual carbon emissions are at record levels, and methods to remove carbon from the atmosphere like bioenergy with carbon capture and storage are still not cost effective.
markets.description_case_no: Total carbon output in some developed countries has been falling for several years now. With global pressure on the growing polluters, like China and India, we may already be past peak carbon output.
markets.underlying: The mean Land-Ocean Temperature Index value reported by NASA’s Goddard Institute for Space Studies (“GISS”). Specifically, the non-smoothed value of the Land-Ocean Temperature Index.

Clarification as of 2:47 PM ET, 10-28-2021: A bill that became law after Issuance and before Expiration imposing an additional tax on personal incomes in excess of some income threshold, conditional on that threshold being greater than or equal to the income threshold necessary to place it in the highest tax bracket, is encompassed in the Payout Criterion. Such a tax (which may be referred to as a “surtax” or “surcharge”) would mean that the bill has the effect of raising the highest personal income tax rate imposed on the highest income tax bracket to be strictly greater than 37%, since the highest tax rate imposed on the bracket would be 37% plus the additional tax.
markets.description_context: Biden came into office promising to raise taxes on the richest Americans. With two new spending bills on the docket and more planned, might he consider raising taxes to pay for them?

markets.description_case_no: Tax hikes are a non-starter among Republicans and possibly some moderate Democrats. Considering the narrow margins in the House and Senate, just a few defections could scuttle any tax increases.

markets.title: Will the Senate pass a bipartisan infrastructure bill before August 10?
markets.ranged_group_name: The bills published on Congress.gov that have the status of “Passed Senate” and the CBO's Cost Estimates.
markets.settle_details:
If a bill that meets the following four conditions is documented on Congress.gov, then the market resolves to Yes. The four conditions are: first, Congress.gov's legislation tracker records that the bill has "Passed Senate" before August 10, 2021; second, that at least sixty Senators voted to pass the bill, as recorded in the "Actions" section of the Congress.gov legislation tracker; third, the CBO's most recent cost estimate for the bill estimates that the bill's total spending for the period 2021-2031 is strictly greater than $600 billion; and fourth, the bill must primarily address the topic of domestic infrastructure, including allocating money to at least three of the following: roads, bridges, rail, broadband, public transit, power infrastructure or water infrastructure as determined by the text of the bill. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see Rule 100.29 in the Rulebook for more information.

Clarification as of 11:30pm ET on August 5, 2021: As noted in the Rulebook, the third condition above relies on a bill's total spending, defined by the greater of the Contract Authority and Budget Authority of the bill, for 2021-2031 as reported by the CBO's most recent cost estimate for the bill.
markets.expiration_value: All bills listed on Congress.gov with the status of “Passed the Senate” that passed the Senate after the time of Issuance and before the Expiration time on the Expiration Date.
markets.underlying: The bills published on Congress.gov that have the status of “Passed Senate” and the CBO's Cost Estimates.

markets.title: Will real GDP increase by more than 6% in Q3?
markets.ranged_group_name: The Advance Estimate of the seasonally adjusted annualized percent change in real GDP from the preceding quarter published by the Bureau of Economic Analysis.
markets.settle_details: If real GDP increases by more than 6% in Q3 2021, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see GDP in the Rulebook for more details.
markets.description_context: Real GDP is a measure of total economic growth. Recent quarterly growth has remained above 6 percent.
markets.description_case_yes: 2021 Q2 growth was above 6 percent and it doesn’t look like it will be slowing down anytime soon. People are returning to the office, supply bottlenecks are loosening and the recent child tax credit has just hit parent’s pockets.
markets.description_case_no: 6% growth is historically extremely high. Previous quarters may just be bounceback from the pandemic and the result of a burst of short-term stimulus spending. With the Delta variant threatening full return-to-office, maintaining 6% growth might be hard.
markets.underlying: The Advance Estimate of the seasonally adjusted annualized percent change in real GDP from the preceding quarter published by the Bureau of Economic Analysis.

markets.title: Will a **recession** start by Q2 2022?
markets.ranged_group_name: The most recent estimates of seasonally adjusted annualized percent changes in quarterly US real GDP from previous quarters as reported by the Bureau of Economic Analysis.
markets.settle_details: If the seasonally adjusted annualized percent change in quarterly U.S. real GDP from the previous quarter is strictly less than zero in at least one of Q3 2021, Q4 2021, Q1 2022, and Q2 2022, then the market resolves to Yes. Else the market resolves to No. Please see RECSS in the Rulebook for more details.
markets.description_context: A recession would be a major blow to Americans’ pocketbooks--one quarter of negative economic growth could wipe out this year’s gains in employment.
markets.description_case_yes: Rising inflation could cause the Fed to tighten monetary policy, causing a recession. Other political risks like a debt ceiling standoff could roil financial markets. Moreover, rising caseloads in the winter may cause further closures and a drop in output.
markets.description_case_no: Recessions are relatively rare. Since 2000, there have been three recessions: in 2001, 2008-2010 and 2020. Moreover, growth is high by historical standards, meaning that growth would have to slow substantially to get negative economic growth.
markets.underlying: The most recent estimates of seasonally adjusted annualized percent changes in quarterly US real GDP from previous quarters as reported by the Bureau of Economic Analysis.

markets.title: Will the Senate pass a reconciliation bill before October 1, 2021?
markets.ranged_group_name: The bills on Congress.gov that have the status of “passed Senate.”
markets.settle_details: If Congress.gov contains documentation of a bill that “passed Senate” after the date of Issuance and before October 1, 2021 and contains reconciliation instructions, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see RECNC in the Rulebook for more details. Such bills typically begin with the phrase “To provide for reconciliation pursuant to…”
markets.description_context: The reconciliation bill likely contains dozens of Biden and Congressional Democrats’ top priorities. There is currently intense negotiation between the progressive and moderate wings of the parties about the size and scope of the bill.
markets.description_case_yes: Moderate members know that they might not hold a trifecta next year and will vote to pass it, even if it isn’t everything they want. With a debt ceiling deadline coming in early October, Democrats may wish to roll the two bills together and get it done in late September.
markets.description_case_no: October 1 is a quick turnaround--there is much negotiation left to be done. Moderates and progressives are still far apart on their priorities and no deal might get done in time.
markets.underlying: The bills on Congress.gov that have the status of “passed Senate.”

markets.title: Will the debt ceiling be raised or suspended before October 1, 2021?

markets.settle_details:
If Congress.gov contains documentation of a bill that “Became Law” after the time of Issuance and before October 1, 2021 and that raises or suspends the current federal debt ceiling, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see DCEIL in the Rulebook for more details.

The current debt limit applicable for this Contract is established by Section 3101(b) of Title 31 of the US Code, which has been modified by the Bipartisan Budget Act of 2019 to stand at roughly $28.5 trillion.

markets.title: Will Drake drop Certified Lover Boy by the end of the summer?
markets.ranged_group_name: The number of Album Units, which includes both album sales and digital streams, earned over the statistical period by Drake’s “Certified Lover Boy” album project, and the album release date, reported to the Exchange pursuant to the Exchange’s agreement with Alpha Data LLC.
markets.settle_details: If, as reported to the Exchange, total consumption of Drake's "Certified Lover Boy" album by 11:59pm ET on September 22, 2021 is greater than zero and the album’s release date is before September 23, 2021, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see DRAKE in the Rulebook for details.
markets.description_context: Drake’s latest album, Certified Lover Boy, has been in the works since 2019. It was originally scheduled to drop in January 2021, but Drake’s knee injury reportedly delayed it. Six months later, he told fans that the album was in the mixing process, adding, “Album’s ready...album’s cooked, looking forward to delivering it to you...Certified Lover Boy on the way and that’s for anyone in the way.”
markets.description_case_yes: Certified Lover Boy was reportedly “ready to go” in October 2020. Back in June, Drake said that Certified Lover Boy would be out by the end of summer. In July, he said it was done and was being mixed that month. Any changes now are probably just finishing touches.
markets.description_case_no: Drake has missed several deadlines already. His last album, Scorpion, had a long promotion period before the drop with singles like “God’s Plan” and “Nice for What”. Without a single since last August, shouldn’t we expect more singles before a release?
markets.underlying: The number of Album Units, which includes both album sales and digital streams, earned over the statistical period by Drake’s “Certified Lover Boy” album project, and the album release date, reported to the Exchange pursuant to the Exchange’s agreement with Alpha Data LLC.

markets.description_context: The price of gas is a critical part of the American economic machine. High gas prices reduce the incentive to travel, reducing demand for businesses who rely on people driving to get to them, like a mall in a suburban town. As a result, it has a large impact on the automobile industry. When gas prices are higher, people tend to try and take more efficient forms of transportation instead, like public transportation. Higher gas prices also create higher costs for almost all businesses, which rely on the shipping of their goods and inputs.

markets.title: Will the bipartisan infrastructure bill become law by September 25, 2021?
markets.ranged_group_name: Bills that have become law, as captured by Congress.gov’s legislation tracker
markets.settle_details: If Congress.gov’s legislation tracker shows that H.R.3684 has “Become Law” by September 25, 2021, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see INFRALW in the Rulebook for details.
markets.description_context: The bipartisan infrastructure bill, once thought to be impossible in the current political climate, passed the evenly-divided Senate with a filibuster-proof majority. However, new risks threaten to sink the bill. Progressives and Moderates have threatened to kill the bill if their demands aren’t met.
markets.description_case_yes: The progressives don’t want to kill the bill, they just want to vote on reconciliation first. Even though the final details of the reconciliation bill might be dictated by Joe Manchin and Krysten Sinema, the Senate’s two most moderate Democrats, the House could still pass a reconciliation bill to set the terms of negotiations to come. Afterwards, the Democrats should approve the infrastructure bill.
markets.description_case_no: The moderates only have nine in their faction, while the progressives have several dozen, so the latter are more likely to win this fight. However, the details of the reconciliation bill will likely be hashed out in the Senate since its moderate members are the ones who might actually oppose it on substance. If the progressives want to vote on that bill first, it may be a while before the infrastructure bill becomes law.
markets.underlying: Bills that have become law, as captured by Congress.gov’s legislation tracker

markets.title: Will the House pass a reconciliation bill before September 25th, 2021?
markets.ranged_group_name: Bills that have passed the House, as captured by Congress.gov’s legislation tracker
markets.settle_details:
If Congress.gov contains documentation of a bill that “passed House” after the date of Issuance and before September 25th, 2021 and contains reconciliation instructions, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see HRECNC in the Rulebook for such details.

Such bills typically begin with the phrase: “To provide for reconciliation pursuant to…"
markets.description_context: The Democrats are trying to pass another large spending bill through the budget reconciliation process to bypass the Senate’s 60-vote filibuster hurdle. However, the legislation is threatened by many, and it’s unclear whether it will be able to become law at all.
markets.description_case_yes: Although nine moderates are threatening to not vote for reconciliation unless they can vote on infrastructure first, most of the Congressional Progressive Caucus’ 96 members have committed to do the reverse. Progressives might need to show power in the wake of several prominent losses this year, such as in the race for the Mayor of New York, and set the terms for reconciliation negotiation in the Senate as soon as possible.
markets.description_case_no: Although the moderates are small in number, their concerns might be louder for the Speaker of the House, Nancy Pelosi, who worries that they are vulnerable to losing their seats to Republicans come 2022. If they win out, expect the vote to be pushed back. In addition, moderate Democratic members of the Senate are likely going to be the ones negotiating the final details with the Biden Administration, so the House might not take up the bill until the Senate is done with it.
markets.underlying: Bills that have passed the House, as captured by Congress.gov’s legislation tracker

markets.title: Will San Francisco public schools remain fully open on October 15?
markets.ranged_group_name: The reopening plans of the San Francisco Unified public school system as posted on the website of the San Francisco Unified public school district.  The exact URL endings may change depending on the format of the announcement.
markets.settle_details:
If San Francisco public schools remain fully open on October 15th, 2021, then the Market resolves to Yes. Else, the Market resolves to No.

For the purposes of this Contract, the criteria for “fully open” are as follows:  Instruction must be available (1) in-person, (2) for generally all students from grades Kindergarten to 12th grade (for details on individual school closures, see product filing), (3) full-time, and (4) five days a week. Further specification of these criteria is on the Product Filings page. 

The Contract will resolve using the reopening plan most recent to Expiration. As of issuance, the reopening plan meets the criteria for a YES resolution.
Please see SFSCHL in the rulebook for more details.
markets.expiration_value: San Francisco schools remain fully open on October 15, 2021
markets.description_context: Last year, San Francisco public schools were largely remote. This Contract gives Members the opportunity to hedge against yet another year of disrupted schools.
markets.description_case_yes: Delta cases continue to rise and the vaccine has still not been authorized for young children.
markets.description_case_no: School closures may anger wide swathes of parents--school officials may fear the backlash if yet another year was lost to Covid.
markets.underlying: The reopening plans of the San Francisco Unified public school system as posted on the website of the San Francisco Unified public school district.  The exact URL endings may change depending on the format of the announcement.

markets.title: Will at least 4 more **hurricanes** make landfall in the USA by December 1?
markets.ranged_group_name: The maximum sustained wind-speeds, locations and times of Atlantic storms at landfall from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration’s National Hurricane Center.
markets.settle_details:
If there are at least 4 storms between Issuance and Expiration Date that (a) have maximum wind speeds equal to or above 74 MPH and (b) make landfall in the United States, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please note that a storm need not have speeds in excess of 74 MPH on or after landfall to qualify. It need only reach the threshold for speed at some point during its existence and also make landfall at some point during its existence. Please see LTHUR in the rulebook for more details. 

Clarification as of 1:30 pm ET on 09/06/2021: "In the United States" is any part of the United States, including Puerto Rico.

settlement_sources.name: National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration’s National Hurricane Center

markets.underlying: The maximum sustained wind-speeds, locations and times of Atlantic storms at landfall from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration’s National Hurricane Center.

markets.title: Will at least one more **major hurricane** make landfall in the USA by December 1?
markets.ranged_group_name: The maximum sustained wind-speeds, locations and times of Atlantic storms at landfall from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration’s National Hurricane Center.
markets.settle_details:
If there is at least one storm between Issuance and Expiration Date that (a) has maximum wind speeds equal to or above 111 MPH and (b) make landfall in the United States, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please note that a storm need not have speeds in excess of 111 MPH on or after landfall to qualify. It need only reach the threshold for speed at some point during its existence and also make landfall at some point during its existence. Please see LTHUR in the rulebook for more details. 

Clarification as of 1:30 pm ET on 09/06/2021: "In the United States" is any part of the United States, including Puerto Rico.

settlement_sources.name: National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration’s National Hurricane Center

markets.underlying: The maximum sustained wind-speeds, locations and times of Atlantic storms at landfall from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration’s National Hurricane Center.

markets.title: Will the CDC identify a **variant of high consequence** by March 1, 2022?
markets.ranged_group_name: The CDC’s SARS-CoV-2 Variant Classifications.
markets.settle_details: If the CDC identifies a variant of high consequence by March 1st, 2022, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to no. Please see VOHC in the rulebook for more details.

settlement_sources.name: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention

markets.description_context: A variant of high consequence, able to nullify much of the effect of the COVID-19 vaccines, would be a major turn for the worse in the pandemic. The CDC has stated that no currently identified variants qualify as one of high consequence--even the Delta variant, which has been classified as a variant of concern.
markets.description_case_yes: Spread of the disease has increased in many nations because of the Delta variant, and the winter--where people will be spending more time indoors--is still yet to come. With more spread expected, there is enough reason to believe that a new, but far worse variant, could arrive in the next six months. At least eight variants have already been identified by the CDC as variants of interest or concern.
markets.description_case_no: The success of the vaccines made sure that the Delta surge resulted in fewer cases and deaths than the case surge during the winter months. With fewer and fewer people expected to get the virus over time, the chances of a variant like this being identified are getting smaller.
markets.underlying: The CDC’s SARS-CoV-2 Variant Classifications.

markets.title: Will the SALT deduction cap be raised before November 15, 2021?
markets.ranged_group_name: Bills that have become law, as captured by Congress.gov.
markets.settle_details:
If a Bill becomes law after Issuance and before November 15, 2021 that increases the current limitation in Internal Revenue Code section 164(b) on the amount allowed as a deduction for state and local taxes in Internal Revenue Code section 164(a) for at least some class of taxpayer, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see the Product Filing for more details. 

Any instructions on how to access the Underlying are provided for convenience only and are not part of the binding Terms and Conditions of the Contract. They may be clarified at any time.
markets.description_context: The state and local tax (SALT) deduction allows households to deduct the amount that they pay in state and local taxes from their federal taxable income. In 2017, the Republican-controlled Congress imposed a cap on the amount that can be deducted of $10,000.
markets.description_case_yes: Many Democrats live in the high-tax jurisdictions that have been hurt by the SALT cap, especially those residing in blue cities within blue states, like New York City. Representatives and Senators from high-tax jurisdictions have been pushing for the cap to be lifted, arguing that many households need to take advantage of deduction in order to justify such high local taxes in the first place.
markets.description_case_no: Senators at the ideological margin, like Joe Manchin, have signalled their interest in paying for new Democratic spending priorities with tax increases. In addition, the SALT deduction is regressive, primarily benefiting high earners who itemize their taxes and pay large amounts of state and local income and property taxes. This strongly fits with the Democratic Party’s commitment to tax the wealthy.
markets.underlying: Bills that have become law, as captured by Congress.gov.

markets.title: Will the debt ceiling be raised or suspended before October 14, 2021?
markets.ranged_group_name: The bills published on Congress.gov that have the status of “Became Law”.
markets.settle_details:
If Congress.gov contains documentation of a bill that “Became Law” after the time of Issuance and before October 14, 2021 and that raises or suspends the current federal debt ceiling, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see DCEIL in the Rulebook for more details.

The current debt limit applicable for this Contract is established by Section 3101(b) of Title 31 of the US Code, which has been modified by the Bipartisan Budget Act of 2019 to stand at roughly $28.5 trillion.

markets.title: Will the FOMC begin tapering at their next meeting?
markets.ranged_group_name: The amount of announced monthly purchases for Treasury Securities and mortgage-backed securities (MBS) by the Federal Reserve Bank of New York (FRBNY) Trading Desk as directed by the Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) statement following their November 02, 2021-November 03, 2021 meeting. If no explicit number is available, the Underlying shall become the sum of the Desk’s plans for purchases of Treasury securities and agency mortgage-backed securities for the most recent period available at Expiration and available for Treasuries and for agency mortgage-backed securities
markets.settle_details: If the FOMC announces in its statement after its November 02, 2021-November 03, 2021 meeting that it directs the FRBNY's trading desk to purchase fewer than $120,000,000,000 in Treasury Securities and MBS per month, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see FTAPER in the rulebook for more details.

settlement_sources.name: Federal Reserve Bank of New York

markets.description_context: Tapering means that the Federal Reserve is going to cut back on its purchase levels.
markets.description_case_yes: Federal Reserve chair Jerome Powell and other members of the Federal Open Market Committee have repeatedly stated that tapering could come soon--but the timing is in question. With inflation still at elevated levels, tapering might come sooner than expected.
markets.description_case_no: Despite elevated inflation, jobs numbers have remained disappointing, perhaps tempering demands to cut back on the Fed's support for the economy.

If no explicit number is available, the Underlying shall become the sum of the Desk’s plans for purchases of Treasury securities and agency mortgage-backed securities for the most recent period available at Expiration and available for Treasuries and for agency mortgage-backed securities

markets.title: Will the FDA authorize a COVID-19 vaccine for children by November 4?
markets.ranged_group_name: Press announcements issued by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA).
markets.settle_details:
If the FDA issues a press announcement authorizing a COVID-19 vaccine to be distributed in the U.S. for use in individuals under 12 years of age by 11:00 AM on November 4, then the market resolves to YES. Press announcements authorizing a COVID-19 for subsets of those under age 12 (such as those “ages 8-11” or “under 12 with certain health conditions”) are encompassed in the Payout Criterion. Such an authorization may take the form of either an FDA approval (licensure) or an emergency use authorization (“EUA”). Else, the market resolves to No. 

Please see KIDVAX in the Rulebook for the legally binding terms and conditions.
markets.expiration_value: The press announcement was on October 29, 2021 and is available here: https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-authorizes-pfizer-biontech-covid-19-vaccine-emergency-use-children-5-through-11-years-age
markets.description_context: Currently, no COVID-19 vaccine is authorized for use in children under the age of 12. Expectations are that this will happen in the future, but it's already been almost a year since the first vaccines were authorized by the FDA for use in adults without much progress.
markets.description_case_yes: Children under 12 include millions of Americans, all of whom are unvaccinated and potentially liable to spread the virus. Given the importance of in-person school, a vaccine for children is imperative to making sure that those they interact with (school staff, their parents) do not get sick.
markets.description_case_no: The fallout of negative side effects in children of a vaccine would be catastrophic for the FDA. Hard-fought credibility would be lost, and it would jeopardize the entire vaccine project to begin with. As a result, the FDA is going to take as much time as possible to study the effects on children before issuing approval.
markets.underlying: Press announcements issued by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA).

markets.title: Will a replacement for **Jerome Powell** be announced by December 1, 2021?
markets.ranged_group_name: Statements from whitehouse.gov. Revisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the Expiration Value.
markets.settle_details: If the White House releases an unretracted statement indicating that an individual other than Jerome Powell will be nominated to be the next Chair of the Federal Reserve by December 1, 2021, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see FEDNOM in the Rulebook for more details.
markets.description_context: Jerome Powell's current term as Chair of the Federal Reserve expires in early 2022. Powell is a Republican nominated by Trump, leading some Democrats to push President Biden for a more liberal replacement.
markets.description_case_yes: President Biden is clearly aligned with the Fed's Democrats. Janet Yellen, who Powell replaced, is on as his Treasury Secretary. He also almost appointed current Fed board member Lael Brainard to that position. In addition, Democrats on the left are pushing him to nominate a Fed Chair more willing to impose financial regulations on banks and take on climate change.
markets.description_case_no: Powell has successfully steered the country out of the COVID-19 induced recession. Market estimates of inflation predict an average of 2.5% over the next five years, more than at any time since prior to the Great Recession. The last thing the President would want to do is rock the boat, and he's unlikely to do it if biggest people pushing for it are on the left fringes of the Democratic Party.
markets.underlying: Statements from whitehouse.gov. Revisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the Expiration Value.

markets.title: Will more than 1.7 million people be screened by the TSA on average this week?

markets.settle_details:

October 03, 2021, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. 

Please be aware that this contract relies on government data as its Underlying that may be impacted by a potential government shutdown. If no data is available at the Source Agency, then the Contract will resolve to No. Per the Rulebook, the Expiration Value shall be calculated using whichever days are available during the period between Monday and Sunday. For example, should no data be available on Friday, Saturday and Sunday, the Expiration Value is the average of Monday-Thursday. Any notice of events such as a potential shutdown is provided for convenience only and might not be issued for future events.

Please see TSAW in the Rulebook for details and the binding terms and conditions. Any instructions on how to access the Underlying as well as guidance on the market page are provided for convenience only and are not part of the binding Terms and Conditions of the Contract. markets.description_context: Geomagnetic storms can wreak havoc on electrical systems and satellites, especially in upper altitudes. Earth last experienced a G1 or greater geomagnetic storm on October 12, 2021.

markets.title: Will a bill imposing a **tax on wealth** or unrealized capital gains become law before December 20, 2021?
markets.ranged_group_name: The text of bills that have become law after Issuance and before December 20, 2021 according to Congress.gov.
markets.settle_details:
If a bill becomes law after Issuance and before December 20, 2021 that imposes a new tax on wealth or unrealized capital gains, then the contract resolves to Yes. Else, the contract resolves to No.

Please see WTAX in the Rulebook for the legally binding terms and conditions, including definitions and examples of eligible taxes.
markets.description_context: The Democrats are scrambling to find a way to pay for their upcoming proposed budget reconciliation bill packed with spending priorities. Senators Krysten Sinema and Joe Manchin have repeatedly shot down a variety of tax increases--but a tax on the wealth of ultramillionaires and/or billionaires might stick.
markets.description_case_yes: A wealth tax on ultramillionaires or billionaires might be the least bad tax to finance Democrats' spending plans. The other commonly mentioned alternatives, like raising corporate taxes, income taxes, or imposing a carbon tax, are all more likely to result in political backlash from voters. There just aren't that many super-rich people to affect next year's election outcomes--and they have a lot of money.
markets.description_case_no: This tax has a variety of implementation problems, and wouldn't raise much revenue as a consequence. Most countries that have implemented wealth taxes repeal them shortly thereafter. Governments have a difficult time valuing the assets of the very wealthy, which are often locked up in opaque claims on long-term income streams and assets, like in private equity funds. Moreover, tax lawyers and billionaires always find a way out of these taxes. It's why high-tax, large welfare states like those in Scandinavia use large, broad-based value-added taxes to finance their large spending.
markets.underlying: The text of bills that have become law after Issuance and before December 20, 2021 according to Congress.gov.

markets.title: Will there be a G1 Geomagnetic storm by November 15, 2021?
markets.ranged_group_name: The maximum Planetary K-index as reported by the Space Weather Prediction Center of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
markets.settle_details:
If the maximum Planetary K-Index between Issuance and November 15, 2021 (inclusive) is at least 5 (equivalent to a G1 geomagnetic storm), then the Contract resolves to Yes. Else, the Contract resolves to No.

Please see GSTORM in the Rulebook for the legally binding terms and conditions, as well as further details about the market.

settlement_sources.name: Space Weather Prediction Center at the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration

markets.description_context: Geomagnetic storms can wreak havoc on electrical systems and satellites, especially in upper altitudes. Some storms, such as the 1859 storm that brought the aurora as far south as New York City, would cause devastating blackouts affecting billions of people. Earth last experienced a G1 or greater geomagnetic storm on October 12, 2021.
markets.underlying: The maximum Planetary K-index as reported by the Space Weather Prediction Center of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.

markets.title: Will the **SALT deduction** cap be raised before December 20, 2021?
markets.ranged_group_name: Bills that have become law, as captured by Congress.gov.
markets.settle_details:
If a Bill becomes law after Issuance and before December 20, 2021 that increases the current limitation in Internal Revenue Code section 164(b) on the amount allowed as a deduction for state and local taxes in Internal Revenue Code section 164(a) for at least some class of taxpayer, then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see the Product Filing for more details.

Any instructions on how to access the Underlying are provided for convenience only and are not part of the binding Terms and Conditions of the Contract. They may be clarified at any time.
markets.description_context: The state and local tax (SALT) deduction allows households to deduct the amount that they pay in state and local taxes from their federal taxable income. In 2017, the Republican-controlled Congress imposed a cap on the amount that can be deducted of $10,000.
markets.description_case_yes: Many Democrats live in the high-tax jurisdictions that have been hurt by the SALT cap, especially those residing in blue cities within blue states, like New York City. Representatives and Senators from high-tax jurisdictions have been pushing for the cap to be lifted, arguing that many households need to take advantage of deduction in order to justify such high local taxes in the first place.
markets.description_case_no: Senators at the ideological margin, like Joe Manchin, have signalled their interest in paying for new Democratic spending priorities with tax increases. In addition, the SALT deduction is regressive, primarily benefiting high earners who itemize their taxes and pay large amounts of state and local income and property taxes. This strongly fits with the Democratic Party’s commitment to tax the wealthy.
markets.underlying: Bills that have become law, as captured by Congress.gov.

markets.title: Will the **bipartisan infrastructure bill** become law by December 20, 2021?

markets.settle_details: If Congress.gov’s legislation tracker shows that H.R.3684 has the status “Became Law” by December 20, 2021 (inclusive), then the market resolves to Yes. Else, the market resolves to No. Please see INFRALW in the Rulebook for details.
markets.underlying: Bills that have become law, as captured by Congress.gov’s legislation tracker

markets.title: Will there be a **G2 Geomagnetic storm** by November 30, 2021?
markets.ranged_group_name: The maximum Planetary K-index as reported by the Space Weather Prediction Center of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
markets.settle_details:
If the maximum Planetary K-Index between Issuance and November 30, 2021 (inclusive) is at least 6 (equivalent to a G2 geomagnetic storm), then the Contract resolves to Yes. Else, the Contract resolves to No.

Please see GSTORM in the Rulebook for the legally binding terms and conditions, as well as further details about the market.

settlement_sources.name: Space Weather Prediction Center at the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration

markets.description_context: Geomagnetic storms can wreak havoc on electrical systems and satellites, especially in upper altitudes. Some storms, such as the 1859 storm that brought the aurora as far south as New York City, would cause devastating blackouts affecting billions of people. Earth last experienced a G1 or greater geomagnetic storm on October 12, 2021.
markets.underlying: The maximum Planetary K-index as reported by the Space Weather Prediction Center of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
